"1334","1311":"1311","Bef 1310":"before 1310","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","ABT 1333":"about 1333","19 JUL 1333":"19 July 1333","1318":"1318","1317":"1317","Carrick, Fife, Scotland":"Carrick, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Berwick-upon-tweed, Northumberland, England":"Berwick-upon-Tweed, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Carrick, Scotland":"Carrick, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Dundalk, County Louth, Ireland":"Dundalk, County Louth, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bruce","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from a place in Normandy, probably from Brix (La Manche).","Altered form of French   Brousse  .","History: The son of the Domesday baron, a friend of David I of Scotland, was granted by him the Lordship of Annandale in 1124, and his second son Robert became the founder of the Scottish house of Bruce. — This surname (see 2 above) is listed along with its original form <i>Brousse</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Brousse","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French: topographic name for someone living in a scrubby area, from Old French <i>bro(u)ce</i> ‘thicket, brushwood’ (from Late Latin <i>bruscia</i>), or a habitational name from any of several places in France named Brousse. Compare   Bruce   and   Brusse  .","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its altered form <i>Bruce</i>) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Brewis","meanings":["English:","(of Norman origin): habitational name from Briouze in Orne.","(Northumberland and Durham): topographic name or nickname from Middle English <i>breuhous</i> ‘brewery’ (literally ‘brew house’)."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander Bruce 1st and last Earl of Carrick was born in 1311, in Carrick, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Edward Bruce Earl of Carrick, High King of Ireland, Lord of Galloway, was 31 and his mother, Isabella de Strathbogie, was 22. He married Eleanor Douglas about 1333, in Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 19 July 1333, in Berwick-upon-Tweed, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 22."},"et":{"1311–19 JUL 1333":"1311–19. juuli 1333","1310–1333":"1310–1333","1311–1333":"1311–1333","1313–1348":"1313–1348","1317–1360":"1317–1360","1334–1368":"1334–1368","1280–1318":"1280–1318","1290–1317":"1290–1317","14 October 1318":"14. oktoober 1318","1360":"1360","1280":"1280","1 Jun 1317":"1. juuni 1317","1290":"1290","1348":"1348","1368":"1368","1313":"1313","1334":"1334","1311":"1311","Bef 1310":"enne 1310","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","ABT 1333":"umbes 1333","19 JUL 1333":"19. juuli 1333","1318":"1318","1317":"1317","Carrick, Fife, Scotland":"Carrick, Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Berwick-upon-tweed, Northumberland, England":"Berwick-upon-Tweed, Northumberlan